## 1. Sensitive Data Protection

- **NEVER** commit API keys, passwords, or tokens directly in code
- Use environment variables for all sensitive configuration
- Include sensitive files in .gitignore (e.g., .env files)
- Alert the user if you detect hardcoded secrets or credentials

## 2. Security Best Practices

- Validate and sanitize all user inputs
- Implement proper authentication and authorization checks
- Follow secure coding practices for the specific language/framework
- Use parameterized queries for database operations to prevent SQL injection

## 3. Dependency Security

- Suggest regular updates for dependencies with known vulnerabilities
- Recommend security scanning tools when appropriate
- Avoid using deprecated or unmaintained libraries

## 4. Secure Configuration

- Add example configuration files with dummy values (e.g., .env.example)
- Document security-related configuration options
- Use secure defaults for all settings

## 5. HTTPS and Secure Communication

- Always use HTTPS for API endpoints
- Implement proper CORS policies
- Set secure headers (Content-Security-Policy, Strict-Transport-Security, etc.)
- Use secure cookies with appropriate flags (Secure, HttpOnly, SameSite)

## 6. Authentication and Authorization

- Implement proper authentication mechanisms
- Use industry standard authentication libraries when possible
- Follow the principle of least privilege for authorization
- Implement proper session management
- Use secure password storage with strong hashing algorithms

## 7. Security Monitoring and Auditing

- Implement proper logging for security events
- Consider adding security monitoring tools
- Regularly audit security practices
- Implement rate limiting for sensitive endpoints